# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bayesian-statistics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] The **Bayes factor** is a ratio of two competing statistical models represented by their evidence, and is used to quantify the support for one model over the other.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] The models in question can have a common set of parameters, such as a null hypothesis and an alternative, but this is not necessary; for instance, it could also be a non-linear model compared to its linear approximation.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] The Bayes factor can be thought of as a Bayesian analog to the likelihood-ratio test, although it uses the integrated (i.e., marginal) likelihood rather than the maximized likelihood.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] As such, both quantities only coincide under simple hypotheses (e.g., two specific parameter values).
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] Also, in contrast with null hypothesis significance testing, Bayes factors support evaluation of evidence *in favor* of a null hypothesis, rather than only allowing the null to be rejected or not rejected.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] Although conceptually simple, the computation of the Bayes factor can be challenging depending on the complexity of the model and the hypotheses.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] Since closed-form expressions of the marginal likelihood are generally not available, numerical approximations based on MCMC samples have been suggested.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] For certain special cases, simplified algebraic expressions can be derived; for instance, the Savage–Dickey density ratio in the case of a precise (equality constrained) hypothesis against an unrestricted alternative.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] Another approximation, derived by applying Laplace's approximation to the integrated likelihoods, is known as the Bayesian information criterion (BIC); in large data sets the Bayes factor will approach the BIC as the influence of the priors wanes.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] In small data sets, priors generally matter and must not be improper since the Bayes factor will be undefined if either of the two integrals in its ratio is not finite.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] The Bayes factor is the ratio of two marginal likelihoods; that is, the likelihoods of two statistical models integrated over the prior probabilities of their parameters.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] The key data-dependent term $\Pr(D|M)$ represents the probability that some data are produced under the assumption of the model *M*; evaluating it correctly is the key to Bayesian model comparison.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] When the two models have equal prior probability, so that $\Pr(M_{1})=\Pr(M_{2})$ , the Bayes factor is equal to the ratio of the posterior probabilities of *M*1 and *M*2.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] If instead of the Bayes factor integral, the likelihood corresponding to the maximum likelihood estimate of the parameter for each statistical model is used, then the test becomes a classical likelihood-ratio test.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] Unlike a likelihood-ratio test, this Bayesian model comparison does not depend on any single set of parameters, as it integrates over all parameters in each model (with respect to the respective priors).
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] An advantage of the use of Bayes factors is that it automatically, and quite naturally, includes a penalty for including too much model structure.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] For models where an explicit version of the likelihood is not available or too costly to evaluate numerically, approximate Bayesian computation can be used for model selection in a Bayesian framework, with the caveat that approximate-Bayesian estimates of Bayes factors are often biased.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] A value of *K* > 1 means that *M*1 is more strongly supported by the data under consideration than *M*2.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] Note that classical hypothesis testing gives one hypothesis (or model) preferred status (the 'null hypothesis'), and only considers evidence *against* it.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] The fact that a Bayes factor can produce evidence *for* and not just against a null hypothesis is one of the key advantages of this analysis method.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] The second column gives the corresponding weights of evidence in decihartleys (also known as decibans); bits are added in the third column for clarity.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] The table continues in the other direction, so that, for example, $K\leq 10^{-2}$ is decisive evidence for $M_{2}$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] Good, the just-noticeable difference of humans in their everyday life, when it comes to a change degree of belief in a hypothesis, is about a factor of 1.3x, or 1 deciban, or 1/3 of a bit, or from 1:1 to 5:4 in odds ratio.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] Suppose we have a random variable that produces either a success or a failure.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] We want to compare a model $M_{1}$ where the probability of success is *q* = 1⁄2, and another model $M_{2}$ where *q* is unknown and we take a prior distribution for *q* that is uniform on [0,1].
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] We take a sample of 200, and find 115 successes and 85 failures.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] The ratio is then 1.2, which is "barely worth mentioning" even if it points very slightly towards $M_{1}$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] A frequentist hypothesis test of $M_{1}$ (here considered as a null hypothesis) would have produced a very different result.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] Such a test says that $M_{1}$ should be rejected at the 5% significance level, since the probability of getting 115 or more successes from a sample of 200 if *q* = 1⁄2 is 0.02, and as a two-tailed test of getting a figure as extreme as or more extreme than 115 is 0.04.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] Note that 115 is more than two standard deviations away from 100.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] Thus, whereas a frequentist hypothesis test would yield significant results at the 5% significance level, the Bayes factor hardly considers this to be an extreme result.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] Note, however, that a non-uniform prior (for example one that reflects that you expect the number of success and failures to be of the same order of magnitude) could result in a Bayes factor that is more in agreement with the frequentist hypothesis test.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] (rather than averaging over all possible *q*).
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] That gives a likelihood ratio of 0.1 and points towards *M*2.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] $M_{2}$ is a more complex model than $M_{1}$ because it has a free parameter which allows it to model the data more closely.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] The ability of Bayes factors to take this into account is a reason why Bayesian inference has been put forward as a theoretical justification for and generalisation of Occam's razor, reducing Type I errors.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] On the other hand, the modern method of relative likelihood takes into account the number of free parameters in the models, unlike the classical likelihood ratio.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] The relative likelihood method could be applied as follows.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] Model *M*1 has 0 parameters, and so its Akaike information criterion (AIC) value is $2\cdot 0-2\cdot \ln(0.005956)\approx 10.2467$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-factor] Thus *M*2 is slightly preferred, but *M*1 cannot be excluded.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem is named after Thomas Bayes, a minister, statistician, and philosopher.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Bayes used conditional probability to provide an algorithm (his Proposition 9) that uses evidence to calculate limits on an unknown parameter.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] His work was published in 1763 as *An Essay Towards Solving a Problem in the Doctrine of Chances*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Bayes studied how to compute a distribution for the probability parameter of a binomial distribution (in modern terminology).
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] After Bayes's death, his family gave his papers to a friend, the minister, philosopher, and mathematician Richard Price.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Price significantly edited the unpublished manuscript for two years before sending it to a friend who read it aloud at the Royal Society on 23 December 1763.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Price edited Bayes's major work "An Essay Towards Solving a Problem in the Doctrine of Chances" (1763), which appeared in *Philosophical Transactions*, and contains Bayes' theorem.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Price wrote an introduction to the paper that provides some of the philosophical basis of Bayesian statistics and chose one of the two solutions Bayes offered.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] In 1765, Price was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society in recognition of his work on Bayes's legacy.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] On 27 April, a letter sent to his friend Benjamin Franklin was read out at the Royal Society, and later published, in which Price applies this work to population and computing 'life-annuities'.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Independently of Bayes, Pierre-Simon Laplace used conditional probability to formulate the relation of an updated posterior probability from a prior probability, given evidence.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] He reproduced and extended Bayes's results in 1774, apparently unaware of Bayes's work, and summarized his results in *Théorie analytique des probabilités* (1812).
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] The Bayesian interpretation of probability was developed mainly by Laplace.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] About 200 years later, Sir Harold Jeffreys put Bayes's algorithm and Laplace's formulation on an axiomatic basis, writing in a 1973 book that Bayes' theorem "is to the theory of probability what the Pythagorean theorem is to geometry".
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Stephen Stigler used a Bayesian argument to conclude that Bayes' theorem was discovered by Nicholas Saunderson, a blind English mathematician, some time before Bayes, but that is disputed.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Thomas Bruss reviewed Bayes's "An essay towards solving a problem in the doctrine of chances" as communicated by Price.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] He agreed with Stigler's analysis on many points, but not on the question of priority.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Bruss underlined the intuitive part of Bayes's formula and added independent arguments about Bayes's probable motivation for his work.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] He concluded that, unless the contrary is proven, the name "Bayes' Theorem" or "Bayes' formula" is justifiable.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] The "Bayes factor" or "likelihood" that appears when writing Bayes' theorem in odds form appears in the early 1940s work of Alan Turing, who called it the "factor in favour of a proposition".
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] In 1878, Charles Sanders Peirce used the logarithm of this factor as the "weight of evidence" for a proposition.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] where A and B are events and $P(B)\neq 0$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem may be derived from the relation between joint and conditional probabilities.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] The events A and not- A , written $\neg A$ , are a mutually exclusive and exhaustive pair.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Suppose that a doctor is testing a patient for the presence of a certain disease.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] The patient either has the disease or does not; the test returns either positive or negative.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Let E be the event that the patient has the disease. $P(E)$ is the probability that the patient has the disease.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Let F be the event that the patient tests positive.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] The probability that the patient has the disease given that they test positive is thus denoted $P(E|F)$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] For example, if all patients with pancreatic cancer have certain symptoms, it does not follow that anyone who has those symptoms has pancreatic cancer.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Assuming the incidence rate of pancreatic cancer is 1/100000, while 10/99999 healthy people have the symptoms, the probability that a person who has the symptoms has pancreatic cancer is 9.1%.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Based on incidence rate, the following table presents the corresponding numbers per 100,000 people.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Suppose a particular test for whether someone has been using a drug (e.g., Substance D) is 99% sensitive, meaning the true positive rate (TPR) = 0.99.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] The test then has 99% true positive results (correct identification of drug use) for drug users.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] The test is also 99% specific, meaning its true negative rate (TNR) = 0.99.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Therefore, the test correctly identifies 99% of non-use for non-users, but also generates 1% false positives, or false positive rate (FPR) = 0.01, for non-users.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] An urn contains coins of three different types: A, B, and C.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Coins of type A are fair and, when flipped, come up heads with probability 0.5.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Coins of type B are biased and have probability 0.6 of turning up heads, and type-C coins come up heads with probability 0.9.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] The urn contains 2 type-A coins, 2 type-B coins and 1 type-C coin.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] A coin is drawn at random from the urn and flipped.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem gives the probability of a coin being of a given type given that it comes up heads: $P(A|H)={\frac {P(H|A)P(A)}{P(H)}},$ and likewise for $P(B|H)$ and $P(C|H)$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] The denominator can be found via the law of total probability: $P(H)=P(H|A)P(A)+P(H|B)P(B)+P(H|C)P(C).$ Assuming the coins are drawn from the urn at random, $P(A)=2/5$ , $P(B)=2/5$ , and $P(C)=1/5$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] The interpretation of Bayes' rule depends on the interpretation of probability ascribed to the terms.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] The two predominant classes of interpretation are described below.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] In Bayesian (or epistemological) interpretations, probability measures a rational "degree of belief".
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem links the degree of belief in a proposition before and after rationally accounting for evidence.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] For example, in a medical testing scenario, if a patient tests positive for a disease, the doctor will find it more plausible that the patient has that disease.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] For more on the application of Bayes' theorem under Bayesian interpretations of probability, see Bayesian inference.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] In the frequentist interpretations, probability measures a "proportion of outcomes".
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] For example, suppose an experiment is performed many times.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] *P*(*A*) is the proportion of outcomes with property *A* (the prior) and *P*(*B*) is the proportion with property *B*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] *P*(*B*|*A*) is the proportion of outcomes with property *B* *out of* outcomes with property *A*, and *P*(*A*|*B*) is the proportion of those with *A* *out of* those with *B* (the posterior).
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] In many applications, for instance in Bayesian inference, the event *B* is fixed in the discussion and we wish to consider the effect of its having been observed on our belief in various possible events *A*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] In such situations the denominator of the last expression, the probability of the given evidence *B*, is fixed; what we want to vary is *A*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] In other words, the posterior is proportional to the prior times the likelihood.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] This holds for values x and y within the support of *X* and *Y*, ensuring $f_{X}(x)>0$ and $f_{Y}(y)>0$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Let $P_{Y}^{x}$ be the conditional distribution of Y given $X=x$ and let $P_{X}$ be the distribution of X .
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Existence and uniqueness of the needed conditional expectation is a consequence of the Radon–Nikodym theorem.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Andrey Kolmogorov formulated this in 1933.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] He underlined the importance of conditional probability, writing, "I wish to call attention to ... the theory of conditional probabilities and conditional expectations".
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem determines the posterior distribution from the prior distribution.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Uniqueness requires continuity assumptions.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem can be generalized to include improper prior distributions such as the uniform distribution on the real line.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Modern Markov chain Monte Carlo methods have boosted the importance of Bayes' theorem, including in cases with improper priors.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Probabilities are sometimes specified in terms of odds.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] For any proposition A , the ratio of the probability that A is true to the probability that A is false is called the odds on A .
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem can be written using odds as follows.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] In symbols: $O(A|B)=O(A){\frac {P(B|A)}{P(B|\neg A)}}.$ This is often summarized by saying that the *posterior odds* are the *prior odds* times the likelihood.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] For example, suppose that a disease has a prevalence of 1%, i.e., the probability that a randomly chosen person is infected is 0.01.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] And suppose that a test for the disease returns the correct result with 99% probability.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] The desired result is obtained by identifying both expressions and solving for $P(A\vert B\cap C)$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] In subjective interpretations of probability theory, an event's probability is regarded as an agent's belief that the event will happen.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem is widely invoked to justify how an agent should update or modify their beliefs after receiving new information.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] If an agent assigns the probability $P(A)$ to the event A , $P(B)$ to the event B , and $P(B|A)$ to the event " B happens assuming A has already happened", Bayes' theorem gives the value of $P(A|B)$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Suppose that, after the agent has made these probability assignments, event B occurs.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] An agent who follows *Bayesian updating,* also known as updating by *conditionalization,* will change their probability for event A from the old value $P(A)$ to the new value $P'(A)=P(A|B)$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Conditionalization is not the only updating rule that might be considered rational.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] The issue of which assumptions can be invoked to constrain updating rules remains somewhat controversial.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] In quantum mechanics, probability distributions are generalized to density matrices, arrays of complex numbers that describe the preparation of a quantum system.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] A *quantum Bayes rule* can be formulated that expresses how density matrices are updated as new experimental data about a system is obtained.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] In Bayesian statistics, an object or system is represented by a mathematical model that contains one or more numerical parameters.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] The available information about the system is used to write a probability distribution over the possible values of those parameters, indicating which values are more plausible than others.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem is then used to update that probability distribution as new evidence is obtained.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Bayes' rule and computing conditional probabilities provide a method to solve a number of popular puzzles, such as the Three Prisoners problem, the Monty Hall problem, the Boy or Girl paradox, and the two envelopes problem.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Alan Turing and his collaborators at Bletchley Park pioneered the use of Bayes' theorem for breaking ciphers during World War II.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] In 1941, Turing wrote a set of pedagogical notes introducing Bayesian methods of cryptanalysis by applying them to problems like solving a Vigenère cipher, which were simpler than his team's primary focus, reading messages encrypted by the Enigma machine.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem was also applied to the cracking of the Japanese naval code JN 25.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] In genetics, Bayes' rule can be used to estimate the probability that someone has a specific genotype.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Many people seek to assess their chances of being affected by a genetic disease or their likelihood of being a carrier for a recessive gene of interest.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] A Bayesian analysis can be done based on family history or genetic testing to predict whether someone will develop a disease or pass one on to their children.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] Bayes' theorem is employed in evolutionary biology to deduce trees of relationships among species that best explain the available data.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayes-theorem] This approach was made practical by the use of Markov chain Monte Carlo methods.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] A **Bayesian network** (also known as a **Bayes network**, **Bayes net**, **belief network**, or **decision network**) is a probabilistic graphical model that represents a set of variables and their conditional dependencies via a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] While it is one of several forms of causal notation, causal networks are special cases of Bayesian networks.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Bayesian networks are ideal for taking an event that occurred and predicting the likelihood that any one of several possible known causes was the contributing factor.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] For example, a Bayesian network could represent the probabilistic relationships between diseases and symptoms.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Given symptoms, the network can be used to compute the probabilities of the presence of various diseases.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Efficient algorithms can perform inference and learning in Bayesian networks.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Bayesian networks that model sequences of variables (*e.g.* speech signals or protein sequences) are called dynamic Bayesian networks.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Generalizations of Bayesian networks that can represent and solve decision problems under uncertainty are called influence diagrams.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Formally, Bayesian networks are directed acyclic graphs (DAGs) whose nodes represent variables in the Bayesian sense: they may be observable quantities, latent variables, unknown parameters or hypotheses.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Each edge represents a direct conditional dependency.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Any pair of nodes that are not connected (i.e. no path connects one node to the other) represent variables that are conditionally independent of each other.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Each node is associated with a probability function that takes, as input, a particular set of values for the node's parent variables, and gives (as output) the probability (or probability distribution, if applicable) of the variable represented by the node.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] For example, if m parent nodes represent m Boolean variables, then the probability function could be represented by a table of $2^{m}$ entries, one entry for each of the $2^{m}$ possible parent combinations.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Similar ideas may be applied to undirected, and possibly cyclic, graphs such as Markov networks.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Suppose we want to model the dependencies between three variables: the sprinkler (or more appropriately, its state - whether it is on or not), the presence or absence of rain and whether the grass is wet or not.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Observe that two events can cause the grass to become wet: an active sprinkler or rain.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Rain has a direct effect on the use of the sprinkler (namely that when it rains, the sprinkler usually is not active).
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] This situation can be modeled with a Bayesian network (shown to the right).
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Each variable has two possible values, T (for true) and F (for false).
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] where *G* = "Grass wet (true/false)", *S* = "Sprinkler turned on (true/false)", and *R* = "Raining (true/false)".
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Using the expansion for the joint probability function $\Pr(G,S,R)$ and the conditional probabilities from the conditional probability tables (CPTs) stated in the diagram, one can evaluate each term in the sums in the numerator and denominator.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] obtained by removing the factor $\Pr(G\mid S,R)$ from the pre-intervention distribution.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] The do operator forces the value of G to be true.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] with the term $\Pr(S=T\mid R)$ removed, showing that the action affects the grass but not the rain.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] These predictions may not be feasible given unobserved variables, as in most policy evaluation problems.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] The effect of the action ${\text{do}}(x)$ can still be predicted, however, whenever the back-door criterion is satisfied.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] A back-door path is one that ends with an arrow into *X*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Sets that satisfy the back-door criterion are called "sufficient" or "admissible." For example, the set *Z* = *R* is admissible for predicting the effect of *S* = *T* on *G*, because *R* *d*-separates the (only) back-door path *S* ← *R* → *G*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] However, if *S* is not observed, no other set *d*-separates this path and the effect of turning the sprinkler on (*S* = *T*) on the grass (*G*) cannot be predicted from passive observations.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] This reflects the fact that, lacking interventional data, the observed dependence between *S* and *G* is due to a causal connection or is spurious (apparent dependence arising from a common cause, *R*).
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Using a Bayesian network can save considerable amounts of memory over exhaustive probability tables, if the dependencies in the joint distribution are sparse.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] For example, a naive way of storing the conditional probabilities of 10 two-valued variables as a table requires storage space for $2^{10}=1024$ values.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] If no variable's local distribution depends on more than three parent variables, the Bayesian network representation stores at most $10\cdot 2^{3}=80$ values.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] One advantage of Bayesian networks is that it is intuitively easier for a human to understand (a sparse set of) direct dependencies and local distributions than complete joint distributions.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Because a Bayesian network is a complete model for its variables and their relationships, it can be used to answer probabilistic queries about them.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] For example, the network can be used to update knowledge of the state of a subset of variables when other variables (the *evidence* variables) are observed.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] This process of computing the *posterior* distribution of variables given evidence is called probabilistic inference.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] The posterior gives a universal sufficient statistic for detection applications, when choosing values for the variable subset that minimize some expected loss function, for instance the probability of decision error.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] A Bayesian network can thus be considered a mechanism for automatically applying Bayes' theorem to complex problems.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] All of these methods have complexity that is exponential in the network's treewidth.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] The most common approximate inference algorithms are importance sampling, stochastic MCMC simulation, mini-bucket elimination, loopy belief propagation, generalized belief propagation and variational methods.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] In order to fully specify the Bayesian network and thus fully represent the joint probability distribution, it is necessary to specify for each node *X* the probability distribution for *X* conditional upon *X*'s parents.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] The distribution of *X* conditional upon its parents may have any form.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] It is common to work with discrete or Gaussian distributions since that simplifies calculations.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Sometimes only constraints on distribution are known; one can then use the principle of maximum entropy to determine a single distribution, the one with the greatest entropy given the constraints.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Often these conditional distributions include parameters that are unknown and must be estimated from data, e.g., via the maximum likelihood approach.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Direct maximization of the likelihood (or of the posterior probability) is often complex given unobserved variables.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] A classical approach to this problem is the expectation-maximization algorithm, which alternates computing expected values of the unobserved variables conditional on observed data, with maximizing the complete likelihood (or posterior) assuming that previously computed expected values are correct.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Under mild regularity conditions, this process converges on maximum likelihood (or maximum posterior) values for parameters.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] A more fully Bayesian approach to parameters is to treat them as additional unobserved variables and to compute a full posterior distribution over all nodes conditional upon observed data, then to integrate out the parameters.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] This approach can be expensive and lead to large dimension models, making classical parameter-setting approaches more tractable.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] In the simplest case, a Bayesian network is specified by an expert and is then used to perform inference.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] In other applications, the task of defining the network is too complex for humans.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] In this case, the network structure and the parameters of the local distributions must be learned from data.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Automatically learning the graph structure of a Bayesian network (BN) is a challenge pursued within machine learning.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] The first 2 represent the same dependencies ( X and Z are independent given Y ) and are, therefore, indistinguishable.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] The collider, however, can be uniquely identified, since X and Z are marginally independent and all other pairs are dependent.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Thus, while the *skeletons* (the graphs stripped of arrows) of these three triplets are identical, the directionality of the arrows is partially identifiable.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] The same distinction applies when X and Z have common parents, except that one must first condition on those parents.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Algorithms have been developed to systematically determine the skeleton of the underlying graph and, then, orient all arrows whose directionality is dictated by the conditional independences observed.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] An alternative method of structural learning uses optimization-based search.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] It requires a scoring function and a search strategy.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] A common scoring function is posterior probability of the structure given the training data, like the BIC or the BDeu.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] The time requirement of an exhaustive search returning a structure that maximizes the score is superexponential in the number of variables.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] A local search strategy makes incremental changes aimed at improving the score of the structure.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] A global search algorithm like Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) can avoid getting trapped in local minima.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Finding a structure that maximizes the mutual information, typically by restricting the parent candidate set to *k* nodes or by finding an optimal *k* on a node-per-node basis, is a technique that consistently achieves high scores on benchmark datasets.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] A particularly fast method for exact BN learning is to cast the problem as an optimization problem, and solve it using integer programming.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Acyclicity constraints are added to the integer program (IP) during solving in the form of cutting planes.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Such method can handle problems with up to 100 variables.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] In order to deal with problems with thousands of variables, a different approach is necessary.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] One is to first sample one ordering, and then find the optimal BN structure with respect to that ordering.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] This implies working on the search space of the possible orderings, which is convenient as it is smaller than the space of network structures.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Multiple orderings are then sampled and evaluated.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] This method has been proven to be the best available in literature when the number of variables is huge.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Another method consists of focusing on the sub-class of decomposable models, for which the MLE have a closed form.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] It is then possible to discover a consistent structure for hundreds of variables.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Learning Bayesian networks with bounded treewidth is necessary to allow exact, tractable inference, since the worst-case inference complexity is exponential in the treewidth k (under the exponential time hypothesis).
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Yet, as a global property of the graph, it considerably increases the difficulty of the learning process.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] In this context it is possible to use K-tree for effective learning.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Given data $x\,\!$ and parameter $\theta$ , a simple Bayesian analysis starts with a prior probability (*prior*) $p(\theta )$ and likelihood $p(x\mid \theta )$ to compute a posterior probability $p(\theta \mid x)\propto p(x\mid \theta )p(\theta )$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Often the prior on $\theta$ depends in turn on other parameters $\varphi$ that are not mentioned in the likelihood.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] This is the simplest example of a *hierarchical Bayes model*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] The process may be repeated; for example, the parameters $\varphi$ may depend in turn on additional parameters $\psi \,\!$ , which require their own prior.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Eventually the process must terminate, with priors that do not depend on unmentioned parameters.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Suppose we are interested in estimating the $\theta _{i}$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] with improper priors $\varphi \sim {\text{flat}}$ , $\tau \sim {\text{flat}}\in (0,\infty )$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] When $n\geq 3$ , this is an *identified model* (i.e. there exists a unique solution for the model's parameters), and the posterior distributions of the individual $\theta _{i}$ will tend to move, or *shrink* away from the maximum likelihood estimates towards their common mean.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] This *shrinkage* is a typical behavior in hierarchical Bayes models.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Some care is needed when choosing priors in a hierarchical model, particularly on scale variables at higher levels of the hierarchy such as the variable $\tau \,\!$ in the example.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] The usual priors such as the Jeffreys prior often do not work, because the posterior distribution will not be normalizable and estimates made by minimizing the expected loss will be inadmissible.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Several equivalent definitions of a Bayesian network have been offered.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] For the following, let *G* = (*V*,*E*) be a directed acyclic graph (DAG) and let *X* = (*X**v*), *v* ∈ *V* be a set of random variables indexed by *V*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] where pa(*v*) is the set of parents of *v* (i.e. those vertices pointing directly to *v* via a single edge).
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] The difference between the two expressions is the conditional independence of the variables from any of their non-descendants, given the values of their parent variables.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] where de(*v*) is the set of descendants and *V* \ de(*v*) is the set of non-descendants of *v*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] The set of parents is a subset of the set of non-descendants because the graph is acyclic.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] In general, learning a Bayesian network from data is known to be NP-hard.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] This is due in part to the combinatorial explosion of enumerating DAGs as the number of variables increases.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Developing a Bayesian network often begins with creating a DAG *G* such that *X* satisfies the local Markov property with respect to *G*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] The conditional probability distributions of each variable given its parents in *G* are assessed.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] In many cases, in particular in the case where the variables are discrete, if the joint distribution of *X* is the product of these conditional distributions, then *X* is a Bayesian network with respect to *G*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] The Markov blanket of a node is the set of nodes consisting of its parents, its children, and any other parents of its children.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] The Markov blanket renders the node independent of the rest of the network; the joint distribution of the variables in the Markov blanket of a node is sufficient knowledge for calculating the distribution of the node.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] *X* is a Bayesian network with respect to *G* if every node is conditionally independent of all other nodes in the network, given its Markov blanket.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] This definition can be made more general by defining the "d"-separation of two nodes, where d stands for directional.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] We first define the "d"-separation of a trail and then we will define the "d"-separation of two nodes in terms of that.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Let *P* be a trail from node *u* to *v*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] A trail is a loop-free, undirected (i.e. all edge directions are ignored) path between two nodes.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] The nodes *u* and *v* are *d*-separated by *Z* if all trails between them are *d*-separated.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] If *u* and *v* are not d-separated, they are d-connected.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] where *Z* is a set which *d*-separates *u* and *v*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Although Bayesian networks are often used to represent causal relationships, this need not be the case: a directed edge from *u* to *v* does not require that *Xv* be causally dependent on *Xu*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] are equivalent: that is they impose exactly the same conditional independence requirements.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] A causal network is a Bayesian network with the requirement that the relationships be causal.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Using these semantics, the impact of external interventions from data obtained prior to intervention can be predicted.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] In 1990, while working at Stanford University on large bioinformatic applications, Cooper proved that exact inference in Bayesian networks is NP-hard.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] This result prompted research on approximation algorithms with the aim of developing a tractable approximation to probabilistic inference.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] In 1993, Paul Dagum and Michael Luby proved two surprising results on the complexity of approximation of probabilistic inference in Bayesian networks.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] First, they proved that no tractable deterministic algorithm can approximate probabilistic inference to within an absolute error *ɛ* < 1/2.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] Second, they proved that no tractable randomized algorithm can approximate probabilistic inference to within an absolute error *ɛ* < 1/2 with confidence probability greater than 1/2.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] The bounded variance algorithm developed by Dagum and Luby was the first provable fast approximation algorithm to efficiently approximate probabilistic inference in Bayesian networks with guarantees on the error approximation.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] This powerful algorithm required the minor restriction on the conditional probabilities of the Bayesian network to be bounded away from zero and one by $1/p(n)$ where $p(n)$ was any polynomial of the number of nodes in the network, n .
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-network] In the late 1980s Pearl's *Probabilistic Reasoning in Intelligent Systems* and Neapolitan's *Probabilistic Reasoning in Expert Systems* summarized their properties and established them as a field of study.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Bayesian statistical methods use Bayes' theorem to compute and update probabilities after obtaining new data.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Bayes' theorem describes the conditional probability of an event based on data as well as prior information or beliefs about the event or conditions related to the event.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] For example, in Bayesian inference, Bayes' theorem can be used to estimate the parameters of a probability distribution or statistical model.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Since Bayesian statistics treats probability as a degree of belief, Bayes' theorem can directly assign a probability distribution that quantifies the belief to the parameter or set of parameters.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Bayesian statistics is named after Thomas Bayes, who formulated a specific case of Bayes' theorem in a paper published in 1763.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] In several papers spanning from the late 18th to the early 19th centuries, Pierre-Simon Laplace developed the Bayesian interpretation of probability.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Laplace used methods now considered Bayesian to solve a number of statistical problems.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] While many Bayesian methods were developed by later authors, the term "Bayesian" was not commonly used to describe these methods until the 1950s.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Throughout much of the 20th century, Bayesian methods were viewed unfavorably by many statisticians due to philosophical and practical considerations.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Many of these methods required much computation, and most widely used approaches during that time were based on the frequentist interpretation.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] However, with the advent of powerful computers and new algorithms like Markov chain Monte Carlo, Bayesian methods have gained increasing prominence in statistics in the 21st century.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Bayes' theorem is used in Bayesian methods to update probabilities, which are degrees of belief, after obtaining new data.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Although Bayes' theorem is a fundamental result of probability theory, it has a specific interpretation in Bayesian statistics.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] The prior probability may also quantify prior knowledge or information about A . $P(B\mid A)$ is the likelihood function, which can be interpreted as the probability of the evidence B given that A is true.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] The likelihood quantifies the extent to which the evidence B supports the proposition A . $P(A\mid B)$ is the posterior probability, the probability of the proposition A after taking the evidence B into account.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Essentially, Bayes' theorem updates one's prior beliefs $P(A)$ after considering the new evidence B .
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] The probability of the evidence $P(B)$ can be calculated using the law of total probability.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] When there are an infinite number of outcomes, it is necessary to integrate over all outcomes to calculate $P(B)$ using the law of total probability.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Often, $P(B)$ is difficult to calculate as the calculation would involve sums or integrals that would be time-consuming to evaluate, so often only the product of the prior and likelihood is considered, since the evidence does not change in the same analysis.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] The maximum a posteriori, which is the mode of the posterior and is often computed in Bayesian statistics using mathematical optimization methods, remains the same.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] The posterior can be approximated even without computing the exact value of $P(B)$ with methods such as Markov chain Monte Carlo or variational Bayesian methods.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Thus, by identifying $Q(\theta \mid x)$ with $\pi (\theta \mid x)$ and ${\mathcal {L}}(x\mid \theta )$ with $P_{\theta }(x)$ we arrive at the classical equation stated above.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] The general set of statistical techniques can be divided into a number of activities, many of which have special Bayesian versions.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Bayesian inference refers to statistical inference where uncertainty in inferences is quantified using probability.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] In classical frequentist inference, model parameters and hypotheses are considered to be fixed.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Probabilities are not assigned to parameters or hypotheses in frequentist inference.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] For example, it would not make sense in frequentist inference to directly assign a probability to an event that can only happen once, such as the result of the next flip of a fair coin.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] However, it would make sense to state that the proportion of heads approaches one-half as the number of coin flips increases.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Statistical models specify a set of statistical assumptions and processes that represent how the sample data are generated.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Statistical models have a number of parameters that can be modified.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] For example, a coin can be represented as samples from a Bernoulli distribution, which models two possible outcomes.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] The Bernoulli distribution has a single parameter equal to the probability of one outcome, which in most cases is the probability of landing on heads.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Devising a good model for the data is central in Bayesian inference.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] In most cases, models only approximate the true process, and may not take into account certain factors influencing the data.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] In Bayesian inference, probabilities can be assigned to model parameters.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Parameters can be represented as random variables.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Bayesian inference uses Bayes' theorem to update probabilities after more evidence is obtained or known.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Furthermore, Bayesian methods allow for placing priors on entire models and calculating their posterior probabilities using Bayes' theorem.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] These posterior probabilities are proportional to the product of the prior and the marginal likelihood, where the marginal likelihood is the integral of the sampling density over the prior distribution of the parameters.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] In complex models, marginal likelihoods are generally computed numerically.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] The formulation of statistical models using Bayesian statistics has the identifying feature of requiring the specification of prior distributions for any unknown parameters.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Indeed, parameters of prior distributions may themselves have prior distributions, leading to Bayesian hierarchical modeling, also known as multi-level modeling.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] For conducting a Bayesian statistical analysis, best practices are discussed by van de Schoot et al.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] The Bayesian design of experiments includes a concept called 'influence of prior beliefs'.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] This approach uses sequential analysis techniques to include the outcome of earlier experiments in the design of the next experiment.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] This is achieved by updating 'beliefs' through the use of prior and posterior distribution.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] This allows the design of experiments to make good use of resources of all types.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] An example of this is the multi-armed bandit problem.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] Exploratory analysis of Bayesian models is an adaptation or extension of the exploratory data analysis approach to the needs and peculiarities of Bayesian modeling.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] The inference process generates a posterior distribution, which has a central role in Bayesian statistics, together with other distributions like the posterior predictive distribution and the prior predictive distribution.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] The correct visualization, analysis, and interpretation of these distributions is key to properly answer the questions that motivate the inference process.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] All these tasks are part of the Exploratory analysis of Bayesian models approach and successfully performing them is central to the iterative and interactive modeling process.
[src:bayesian-statistics/bayesian-statistics] These tasks require both numerical and visual summaries.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] A conjugate prior is an algebraic convenience, giving a closed-form expression for the posterior; otherwise, numerical integration may be necessary.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] Further, conjugate priors may clarify how a likelihood function updates a prior distribution.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] The concept, as well as the term "conjugate prior", were introduced by Howard Raiffa and Robert Schlaifer in their work on Bayesian decision theory.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] A similar concept had been discovered independently by George Alfred Barnard.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] The form of the conjugate prior can generally be determined by inspection of the probability density or probability mass function of a distribution.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] For example, consider a random variable which consists of the number of successes s in n Bernoulli trials with *unknown* probability of success q in [0,1].
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] where $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are chosen to reflect any existing belief or information ( $\alpha =1$ and $\beta =1$ would give a uniform distribution) and $\mathrm {B} (\alpha ,\beta )$ is the Beta function acting as a normalising constant.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] In this context, $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are called *hyperparameters* (parameters of the prior), to distinguish them from parameters of the underlying model (here q ).
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] A typical characteristic of conjugate priors is that the dimensionality of the hyperparameters is one greater than that of the parameters of the original distribution.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] If all parameters are scalar values, then there will be one more hyperparameter than parameter; but this also applies to vector-valued and matrix-valued parameters.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] which is another Beta distribution with parameters $(\alpha +s,\beta +f)$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] This posterior distribution could then be used as the prior for more samples, with the hyperparameters simply adding each extra piece of information as it comes.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] It is often useful to think of the hyperparameters of a conjugate prior distribution corresponding to having observed a certain number of *pseudo-observations* with properties specified by the parameters.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] In general, for nearly all conjugate prior distributions, the hyperparameters can be interpreted in terms of pseudo-observations.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] This can help provide intuition behind the often messy update equations and help choose reasonable hyperparameters for a prior.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] Starting at different points yields different flows over time.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] This is again analogous with the dynamical system defined by a linear operator, but note that since different samples lead to different inferences, this is not simply dependent on time but rather on data over time.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] For related approaches, see Recursive Bayesian estimation and Data assimilation.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] Suppose a rental car service operates in your city.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] Drivers can drop off and pick up cars anywhere inside the city limits.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] You can find and rent cars using an app.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] Suppose you wish to find the probability that you can find a rental car within a short distance of your home address at any time of day.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] Suppose we assume the data comes from a Poisson distribution.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] This is the Poisson distribution that is *the* most likely to have generated the observed data $\mathbf {x}$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] But the data could also have come from another Poisson distribution, e.g., one with $\lambda =3$ , or $\lambda =2$ , etc.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] In fact, there is an infinite number of Poisson distributions that *could* have generated the observed data.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] With relatively few data points, we should be quite uncertain about which exact Poisson distribution generated this data.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] Intuitively we should instead take a weighted average of the probability of $p(x>0|\lambda )$ for each of those Poisson distributions, weighted by how likely they each are, given the data we've observed $\mathbf {x}$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] Generally, this quantity is known as the posterior predictive distribution $p(x|\mathbf {x} )=\int _{\theta }p(x|\theta )p(\theta |\mathbf {x} )d\theta \,,$ where x is a new data point, $\mathbf {x}$ is the observed data and $\theta$ are the parameters of the model.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] Using Bayes' theorem we can expand $p(\theta |\mathbf {x} )={\frac {p(\mathbf {x} |\theta )p(\theta )}{p(\mathbf {x} )}}\,,$ therefore $p(x|\mathbf {x} )=\int _{\theta }p(x|\theta ){\frac {p(\mathbf {x} |\theta )p(\theta )}{p(\mathbf {x} )}}d\theta \,.$ Generally, this integral is hard to compute.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] However, if you choose a conjugate prior distribution $p(\theta )$ , a closed-form expression can be derived.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] This is the posterior predictive column in the tables below.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] Returning to our example, if we pick the Gamma distribution as our prior distribution over the rate of the Poisson distributions, then the posterior predictive is the negative binomial distribution, as can be seen from the table below.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] The Gamma distribution is parameterized by two hyperparameters $\alpha ,\beta$ , which we have to choose.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] By looking at plots of the gamma distribution, we pick $\alpha =\beta =2$ , which seems to be a reasonable prior for the average number of cars.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] The choice of prior hyperparameters is inherently subjective and based on prior knowledge.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] This much more conservative estimate reflects the uncertainty in the model parameters, which the posterior predictive takes into account.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] Let *n* denote the number of observations.
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] In all cases below, the data is assumed to consist of *n* points $x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}$ (which will be random vectors in the multivariate cases).
[src:bayesian-statistics/conjugate-prior] If the likelihood function belongs to the exponential family, then a conjugate prior exists, often also in the exponential family; see Exponential family: Conjugate distributions.
[src:bayesian-statistics/credible-interval] In Bayesian statistics, a **credible interval** is an interval used to characterize a probability distribution.
[src:bayesian-statistics/credible-interval] It is defined such that an unobserved parameter value has a particular probability $\gamma$ to fall within it.
[src:bayesian-statistics/credible-interval] For example, in an experiment that determines the distribution of possible values of the parameter $\mu$ , if the probability that $\mu$ lies between 35 and 45 is $\gamma =0.95$ , then $35\leq \mu \leq 45$ is a 95% credible interval.
[src:bayesian-statistics/credible-interval] Credible intervals are typically used to characterize posterior probability distributions or predictive probability distributions.
[src:bayesian-statistics/credible-interval] Their generalization to disconnected or multivariate sets is called **credible set** or credible region.
[src:bayesian-statistics/credible-interval] Credible intervals are a Bayesian analog to confidence intervals in frequentist statistics.
[src:bayesian-statistics/credible-interval] The two concepts arise from different philosophies: Bayesian intervals treat their bounds as fixed and the estimated parameter as a random variable, whereas frequentist confidence intervals treat their bounds as random variables and the parameter as a fixed value.
[src:bayesian-statistics/credible-interval] Also, Bayesian credible intervals use (and indeed, require) knowledge of the situation-specific prior distribution, while the frequentist confidence intervals do not.
[src:bayesian-statistics/credible-interval] Credible sets are not unique, as any given probability distribution has an infinite number of $\gamma$ -credible sets, i.e. sets of probability $\gamma$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/credible-interval] One may also define an interval for which the mean is the central point, assuming that the mean exists.
[src:bayesian-statistics/credible-interval] $\gamma$ -Smallest Credible Sets ( $\gamma$ -SCS) can easily be generalized to the multivariate case, and are bounded by probability density contour lines.
[src:bayesian-statistics/credible-interval] They always contain the mode, but not necessarily the mean, the coordinate-wise median, nor the geometric median.
[src:bayesian-statistics/credible-interval] Credible intervals can also be estimated through the use of simulation techniques such as Markov chain Monte Carlo.
[src:bayesian-statistics/credible-interval] A frequentist 95% confidence interval means that with a large number of repeated samples, 95% of such calculated confidence intervals would include the true value of the parameter.
[src:bayesian-statistics/credible-interval] In frequentist terms, the parameter is *fixed* (cannot be considered to have a distribution of possible values) and the confidence interval is *random* (as it depends on the random sample).
[src:bayesian-statistics/credible-interval] But these are distinctly special (albeit important) cases; in general no such equivalence can be made.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] The **posterior probability** is a type of conditional probability that results from updating the prior probability with information summarized by the likelihood via an application of Bayes' rule.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] From an epistemological perspective, the posterior probability contains everything there is to know about an uncertain proposition (such as a scientific hypothesis, or parameter values), given prior knowledge and a mathematical model describing the observations available at a particular time.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] After the arrival of new information, the current posterior probability may serve as the prior in another round of Bayesian updating.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] In the context of Bayesian statistics, the **posterior probability distribution** usually describes the epistemic uncertainty about statistical parameters conditional on a collection of observed data.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] From a given posterior distribution, various point and interval estimates can be derived, such as the maximum a posteriori (MAP) or the highest posterior density interval (HPDI).
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] But while conceptually simple, the posterior distribution is generally not tractable and therefore needs to be either analytically or numerically approximated.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] In Bayesian statistics, the posterior probability is the probability distribution of the parameters $\theta$ given the evidence X , and is denoted $p(\theta |X)$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] It contrasts with the likelihood function, which is the probability of the evidence given the parameters: $p(X|\theta )$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] for continuous $\theta$ , or by summing $p(x|\theta )p(\theta )$ over all possible values of $\theta$ for discrete $\theta$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] The posterior probability is therefore proportional to the product *Likelihood · Prior probability*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] Suppose there is a school with 60% boys and 40% girls as students.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] The girls wear trousers or skirts in equal numbers; all boys wear trousers.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] An observer sees a (random) student from a distance; all the observer can see is that this student is wearing trousers.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] What is the probability this student is a girl?
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] The correct answer can be computed using Bayes' theorem.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] The event G is that the student observed is a girl, and the event T is that the student observed is wearing trousers.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] An intuitive way to solve this is to assume the school has *N* students.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] Number of boys = 0.6*N* and number of girls = 0.4*N*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] If *N* is large enough that rounding errors can be ignored, total number of trouser wearers = 0.6*N* + 50% of 0.4*N*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] And number of girl trouser wearers = 50% of 0.4*N*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] In other words, if you separated out the group of trouser wearers, a quarter of that group will be girls.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] Therefore, if you see trousers, the most you can deduce is that you are looking at a single sample from a subset of students where 25% are girls.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] And by definition, chance of this random student being a girl is 25%.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] Every Bayes-theorem problem can be solved in this way.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] Posterior probability is a conditional probability conditioned on randomly observed data.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] For a random variable, it is important to summarize its amount of uncertainty.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] One way to achieve this goal is to provide a credible interval of the posterior probability.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] In classification, posterior probabilities reflect the uncertainty of assessing an observation to particular class, see also class-membership probabilities.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] While statistical classification methods by definition generate posterior probabilities, Machine Learners usually supply membership values which do not induce any probabilistic confidence.
[src:bayesian-statistics/posterior-probability] It is desirable to transform or rescale membership values to class-membership probabilities, since they are comparable and additionally more easily applicable for post-processing.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] A **prior probability distribution** (often simply called the **prior probability**, **prior distribution**, or **prior**) of an uncertain quantity is its assumed probability distribution before evidence is taken into account.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] For example, the prior could be the probability distribution representing the relative proportions of voters who will vote for a particular politician in a future election.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The unknown quantity may be a parameter of the model or a latent variable rather than an observable variable.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In Bayesian statistics, Bayes' rule prescribes how to update the prior with new information to obtain the posterior probability distribution, which is the conditional distribution of the uncertain quantity given new data.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Historically, the choice of priors was often constrained to a conjugate family of a given likelihood function, so that it would result in a tractable posterior of the same family.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The widespread availability of Markov chain Monte Carlo methods, however, has made this less of a concern.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] There are many ways to construct a prior distribution.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In some cases, a prior may be determined from past information, such as previous experiments.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] A prior can also be *elicited* from the purely subjective assessment of an experienced expert.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] When no information is available, an **uninformative prior** may be adopted as justified by the principle of indifference.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In modern applications, priors are also often chosen for their mechanical properties, such as regularization and feature selection.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The prior distributions of model parameters will often depend on parameters of their own.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Uncertainty about these hyperparameters can, in turn, be expressed as hyperprior probability distributions.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In principle, priors can be decomposed into many conditional levels of distributions, so-called *hierarchical priors*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] An *informative prior* expresses specific, definite information about a variable.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] An example is a prior distribution for the temperature at noon tomorrow.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] A reasonable approach is to make the prior a normal distribution with expected value equal to today's noontime temperature, with variance equal to the day-to-day variance of atmospheric temperature, or a distribution of the temperature for that day of the year.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The terms "prior" and "posterior" are generally relative to a specific datum or observation.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] A **strong prior** is a preceding assumption, theory, concept or idea upon which, after taking account of new information, a current assumption, theory, concept or idea is founded.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] A strong prior is a type of informative prior in which the information contained in the prior distribution dominates the information contained in the data being analyzed.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The Bayesian analysis combines the information contained in the prior with that extracted from the data to produce the posterior distribution which, in the case of a "strong prior", would be little changed from the prior distribution.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] A *weakly informative prior* expresses partial information about a variable, steering the analysis toward solutions that align with existing knowledge without overly constraining the results and preventing extreme estimates.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] An example is, when setting the prior distribution for the temperature at noon tomorrow in St.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Louis, to use a normal distribution with mean 50 degrees Fahrenheit and standard deviation 40 degrees, which very loosely constrains the temperature to the range (10 degrees, 90 degrees) with a small chance of being below -30 degrees or above 130 degrees.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The purpose of a weakly informative prior is for regularization, that is, to keep inferences in a reasonable range.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] An *uninformative*, *flat*, or *diffuse prior* expresses vague or general information about a variable.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The term "uninformative prior" is somewhat of a misnomer.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Such a prior might also be called a *not very informative prior*, or an *objective prior*, i.e., one that is not subjectively elicited.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Uninformative priors can express "objective" information such as "the variable is positive" or "the variable is less than some limit".
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The simplest and oldest rule for determining a non-informative prior is the principle of indifference, which assigns equal probabilities to all possibilities.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In parameter estimation problems, the use of an uninformative prior typically yields results which are not too different from conventional statistical analysis, as the likelihood function often yields more information than the uninformative prior.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Perhaps the strongest arguments for objective Bayesianism were given by Edwin T.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Jaynes, based mainly on the consequences of symmetries and on the principle of maximum entropy.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] As an example of an a priori prior, due to Jaynes (2003), consider a situation in which one knows a ball has been hidden under one of three cups, A, B, or C, but no other information is available about its location.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In this case a *uniform prior* of *p*(*A*) = *p*(*B*) = *p*(*C*) = 1/3 seems intuitively like the only reasonable choice.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] More formally, we can see that the problem remains the same if we swap around the labels ("A", "B" and "C") of the cups.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] It would therefore be odd to choose a prior for which a permutation of the labels would cause a change in our predictions about which cup the ball will be found under; the uniform prior is the only one which preserves this invariance.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] If one accepts this invariance principle then one can see that the uniform prior is the logically correct prior to represent this state of knowledge.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] As a more contentious example, Jaynes published an argument based on the invariance of the prior under a change of parameters that suggests that the prior representing complete uncertainty about a probability should be the Haldane prior *p*−1(1 − *p*)−1.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The example Jaynes gives is of finding a chemical in a lab and asking whether it will dissolve in water in repeated experiments.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The Haldane prior gives by far the most weight to $p=0$ and $p=1$ , indicating that the sample will either dissolve every time or never dissolve, with equal probability.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] However, if one has observed samples of the chemical to dissolve in one experiment and not to dissolve in another experiment then this prior is updated to the uniform distribution on the interval [0, 1].
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] This is obtained by applying Bayes' theorem to the data set consisting of one observation of dissolving and one of not dissolving, using the above prior.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The Haldane prior is an improper prior distribution (meaning that it has an infinite mass).
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Harold Jeffreys devised a systematic way for designing uninformative priors as e.g., Jeffreys prior *p*−1/2(1 − *p*)−1/2 for the Bernoulli random variable.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Priors can be constructed which are proportional to the Haar measure if the parameter space *X* carries a natural group structure which leaves invariant our Bayesian state of knowledge.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] This can be seen as a generalisation of the invariance principle used to justify the uniform prior over the three cups in the example above.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] For example, in physics we might expect that an experiment will give the same results regardless of our choice of the origin of a coordinate system.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] This induces the group structure of the translation group on *X*, which determines the prior probability as a constant improper prior.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Similarly, some measurements are naturally invariant to the choice of an arbitrary scale (e.g., whether centimeters or inches are used, the physical results should be equal).
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In such a case, the scale group is the natural group structure, and the corresponding prior on *X* is proportional to 1/*x*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] It sometimes matters whether we use the left-invariant or right-invariant Haar measure.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] For example, the left and right invariant Haar measures on the affine group are not equal.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] 413) argues that the right-invariant Haar measure is the correct choice.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Jaynes, is to use the principle of maximum entropy (MAXENT).
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The motivation is that the Shannon entropy of a probability distribution measures the amount of information contained in the distribution.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The larger the entropy, the less information is provided by the distribution.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Thus, by maximizing the entropy over a suitable set of probability distributions on *X*, one finds the distribution that is least informative in the sense that it contains the least amount of information consistent with the constraints that define the set.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] For example, the maximum entropy prior on a discrete space, given only that the probability is normalized to 1, is the prior that assigns equal probability to each state.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] And in the continuous case, the maximum entropy prior given that the density is normalized with mean zero and unit variance is the standard normal distribution.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The principle of *minimum cross-entropy* generalizes MAXENT to the case of "updating" an arbitrary prior distribution with suitable constraints in the maximum-entropy sense.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] A related idea, reference priors, was introduced by José-Miguel Bernardo.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Here, the idea is to maximize the expected Kullback–Leibler divergence of the posterior distribution relative to the prior.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] This maximizes the expected posterior information about *X* when the prior density is *p*(*x*); thus, in some sense, *p*(*x*) is the "least informative" prior about X.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The reference prior is defined in the asymptotic limit, i.e., one considers the limit of the priors so obtained as the number of data points goes to infinity.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Here, t is a sufficient statistic for some parameter x .
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The inner integral is the KL divergence between the posterior $p(x\mid t)$ and prior $p(x)$ distributions and the result is the weighted mean over all values of t .
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The inner integral in the second part is the integral over t of the joint density $p(x,t)$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In words, KL is the negative expected value over t of the entropy of x conditional on t plus the marginal (i.e., unconditional) entropy of x .
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In the limiting case where the sample size tends to infinity, the Bernstein-von Mises theorem states that the distribution of x conditional on a given observed value of t is normal with a variance equal to the reciprocal of the Fisher information at the 'true' value of x .
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The entropy of a normal density function is equal to half the logarithm of $2\pi ev$ where v is the variance of the distribution.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In this case therefore $H=\log {\sqrt {\frac {2\pi e}{NI(x^{*})}}}$ where N is the arbitrarily large sample size (to which Fisher information is proportional) and $x*$ is the 'true' value.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Since this does not depend on t it can be taken out of the integral, and as this integral is over a probability space it equals one.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Hence we can write the asymptotic form of KL as $KL=-\log \left(1{\sqrt {kI(x^{*})}}\right)-\,\int p(x)\log[p(x)]\,dx$ where k is proportional to the (asymptotically large) sample size.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Indeed, the very idea goes against the philosophy of Bayesian inference in which 'true' values of parameters are replaced by prior and posterior distributions.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] So we remove $x*$ by replacing it with x and taking the expected value of the normal entropy, which we obtain by multiplying by $p(x)$ and integrating over x .
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] This is a quasi-KL divergence ("quasi" in the sense that the square root of the Fisher information may be the kernel of an improper distribution).
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Due to the minus sign, we need to minimise this in order to maximise the KL divergence with which we started.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The minimum value of the last equation occurs where the two distributions in the logarithm argument, improper or not, do not diverge.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] This in turn occurs when the prior distribution is proportional to the square root of the Fisher information of the likelihood function.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Hence in the single parameter case, reference priors and Jeffreys priors are identical, even though Jeffreys has a very different rationale.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Reference priors are often the objective prior of choice in multivariate problems, since other rules (e.g., Jeffreys' rule) may result in priors with problematic behavior.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Objective prior distributions may also be derived from other principles, such as information or coding theory (see e.g., minimum description length) or frequentist statistics (so-called probability matching priors).
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Such methods are used in Solomonoff's theory of inductive inference.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Constructing objective priors have been recently introduced in bioinformatics, and specially inference in cancer systems biology, where sample size is limited and a vast amount of **prior knowledge** is available.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In these methods, either an information theory based criterion, such as KL divergence or log-likelihood function for binary supervised learning problems and mixture model problems.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Philosophical problems associated with uninformative priors are associated with the choice of an appropriate metric, or measurement scale.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Suppose we want a prior for the running speed of a runner who is unknown to us.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] We could specify, say, a normal distribution as the prior for his speed, but alternatively we could specify a normal prior for the time he takes to complete 100 metres, which is proportional to the reciprocal of the first prior.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] These are very different priors, but it is not clear which is to be preferred.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Jaynes' method of transformation groups can answer this question in some situations.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Similarly, if asked to estimate an unknown proportion between 0 and 1, we might say that all proportions are equally likely, and use a uniform prior.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Alternatively, we might say that all orders of magnitude for the proportion are equally likely, the **logarithmic prior**, which is the uniform prior on the logarithm of proportion.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The Jeffreys prior attempts to solve this problem by computing a prior which expresses the same belief no matter which metric is used.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The Jeffreys prior for an unknown proportion *p* is *p*−1/2(1 − *p*)−1/2, which differs from Jaynes' recommendation.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Priors based on notions of algorithmic probability are used in inductive inference as a basis for induction in very general settings.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Practical problems associated with uninformative priors include the requirement that the posterior distribution be proper.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The usual uninformative priors on continuous, unbounded variables are improper.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] This need not be a problem if the posterior distribution is proper.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Another issue of importance is that if an uninformative prior is to be used *routinely*, i.e., with many different data sets, it should have good frequentist properties.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Normally a Bayesian would not be concerned with such issues, but it can be important in this situation.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] For example, one would want any decision rule based on the posterior distribution to be admissible under the adopted loss function.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Admissibility is often difficult to check, although some results are known (e.g., Berger and Strawderman 1996).
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The issue is particularly acute with hierarchical Bayes models; the usual priors (e.g., Jeffreys' prior) may give badly inadmissible decision rules if employed at the higher levels of the hierarchy.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Let events $A_{1},A_{2},\ldots ,A_{n}$ be mutually exclusive and exhaustive.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] If the summation in the denominator converges, the posterior probabilities will still sum (or integrate) to 1 even if the prior values do not, and so the priors may only need to be specified in the correct proportion.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Taking this idea further, in many cases the sum or integral of the prior values may not even need to be finite to get sensible answers for the posterior probabilities.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] When this is the case, the prior is called an **improper prior**.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] However, the posterior distribution need not be a proper distribution if the prior is improper.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] This is clear from the case where event *B* is independent of all of the *A**j*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Statisticians sometimes use improper priors as uninformative priors.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Many authors (Lindley, 1973; De Groot, 1937; Kass and Wasserman, 1996) warn against the danger of over-interpreting those priors since they are not probability densities.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The only relevance they have is found in the corresponding posterior, as long as it is well-defined for all observations.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] By contrast, likelihood functions do not need to be integrated, and a likelihood function that is uniformly 1 corresponds to the absence of data (all models are equally likely, given no data): Bayes' rule multiplies a prior by the likelihood, and an empty product is just the constant likelihood 1.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] However, without starting with a prior probability distribution, one does not end up getting a posterior probability distribution, and thus cannot integrate or compute expected values or loss.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] See Likelihood function § Non-integrability for details.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] These functions, interpreted as uniform distributions, can also be interpreted as the likelihood function in the absence of data, but are not proper priors.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] While in Bayesian statistics the prior probability is used to represent initial beliefs about an uncertain parameter, in statistical mechanics the a priori probability is used to describe the initial state of a system.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The classical version is defined as the ratio of the number of elementary events (e.g., the number of times a die is thrown) to the total number of events—and these considered purely deductively, i.e., without any experimenting.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In the case of the die if we look at it on the table without throwing it, each elementary event is reasoned deductively to have the same probability—thus the probability of each outcome of an imaginary throwing of the (perfect) die or simply by counting the number of faces is 1/6.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Each face of the die appears with equal probability—probability being a measure defined for each elementary event.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The result is different if we throw the die twenty times and ask how many times (out of 20) the number 6 appears on the upper face.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In this case time comes into play and we have a different type of probability depending on time or the number of times the die is thrown.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] On the other hand, the a priori probability is independent of time—you can look at the die on the table as long as you like without touching it and you deduce the probability for the number 6 to appear on the upper face is 1/6.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In statistical mechanics, e.g., that of a gas contained in a finite volume V , both the spatial coordinates $q_{i}$ and the momentum coordinates $p_{i}$ of the individual gas elements (atoms or molecules) are finite in the phase space spanned by these coordinates.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In 1 dimension (length L ) this number or statistical weight or a priori weighting is $L\Delta p/h$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In customary 3 dimensions (volume V ) the corresponding number can be calculated to be $V4\pi p^{2}\Delta p/h^{3}$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In order to understand this quantity as giving a number of states in quantum (i.e., wave) mechanics, recall that in quantum mechanics every particle is associated with a matter wave which is the solution of a Schrödinger equation.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In the case of free particles (of energy $\epsilon ={\bf {p}}^{2}/2m$ ) like those of a gas in a box of volume $V=L^{3}$ such a matter wave is explicitly $\psi \propto \sin {\frac {l\pi x}{L}}\sin {\frac {m\pi y}{L}}\sin {\frac {n\pi z}{L}},$ where $l,m,n$ are integers.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The number of different $(l,m,n)$ values and hence states in the region between $p,p+dp,p^{2}={\bf {p}}^{2},$ is then found to be the above expression $V4\pi p^{2}dp/h^{3}$ by considering the area covered by these points.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Moreover, in view of the uncertainty relation, which in 1 spatial dimension is $\Delta q\Delta p\geq h,$ these states are indistinguishable (i.e., these states do not carry labels).
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] An important consequence is a result known as Liouville's theorem, i.e., the time independence of this phase space volume element and thus of the a priori probability.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] A time dependence of this quantity would imply known information about the dynamics of the system, and hence would not be an a priori probability.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Thus the region ${\displaystyle \Omega$ when differentiated with respect to time t yields zero (with the help of Hamilton's equations): The volume at time t is the same as at time zero.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] One describes this also as conservation of information.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In the full quantum theory one has an analogous conservation law.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In this case, the phase space region is replaced by a subspace of the space of states expressed in terms of a projection operator P , and instead of the probability in phase space, one has the probability density ${\displaystyle \Sigma$ where N is the dimensionality of the subspace.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The conservation law in this case is expressed by the unitarity of the S-matrix.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In either case, the considerations assume a closed isolated system.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] This closed isolated system is a system with (1) a fixed energy E and (2) a fixed number of particles N in (c) a state of equilibrium.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] If one considers a huge number of replicas of this system, one obtains what is called a *microcanonical ensemble*.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] It is for this system that one postulates in quantum statistics the "fundamental postulate of equal a priori probabilities of an isolated system." This says that the isolated system in equilibrium occupies each of its accessible states with the same probability.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] This fundamental postulate therefore allows us to equate the a priori probability to the degeneracy of a system, i.e., to the number of different states with the same energy.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] The following example illustrates the a priori probability (or a priori weighting) in (a) classical and (b) quantal contexts.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] From wave mechanics it is known that the energy levels of a rotating diatomic molecule are given by $E_{n}={\frac {n(n+1)h^{2}}{8\pi ^{2}I}},$ each such level being (2n+1)-fold degenerate.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In the case of the one-dimensional simple harmonic oscillator of natural frequency $\nu$ one finds correspondingly: (a) $\Omega \propto dE/\nu$ , and (b) $\Sigma \propto dn$ (no degeneracy).
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Thus in quantum mechanics the a priori probability is effectively a measure of the degeneracy, i.e. the number of states having the same energy.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In the case of the hydrogen atom or Coulomb potential (where the evaluation of the phase space volume for constant energy is more complicated) one knows that the quantum mechanical degeneracy is $n^{2}$ with $E\propto 1/n^{2}$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Thus in this case $\Sigma \propto n^{2}dn$ .
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] In statistical mechanics, it is common to derive so-called distribution functions f for various statistics.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] An important aspect in the derivation is the taking into account of the indistinguishability of particles and states in quantum statistics, i.e., there particles and states do not have labels.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] On the other hand, the a priori probability $g_{i}$ is a measure of the number of wave mechanical states available.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Above no mention was made of electric or other fields.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] Thus with no such fields present we have the Fermi-Dirac distribution as above.
[src:bayesian-statistics/prior-probability] But with such fields present we have this additional dependence of f .
